{"type":"message","id":"edb70408","parentId":"525a989d","timestamp":"2026-04-15T02:55:20.519Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have both the current sessions list and the last heartbeat state. Let me compare them carefully.\n\n**Last known state (02:46 UTC):**\n- cron:6f3323ef (DTLX 5p Monitor): running, ~6h 2m\n- cron:ed2d0b5d (QLHV 5p monitor): running, active cycle\n- cron:e7885813 (Agent Status to Lead): running, recovered, new cycle running\n- cron:ac986a8d (Telegram send cron): orphaned, ~22h stale\n- cron:53c5832a (Daily Briefing): done (expected)\n\n\n- main: done (HEARTBEAT_OK at 02:17 UTC)\n- telegram:direct:6053576134: running, idle\n- telegram:group:-5163901258: running, idle (last 5p report 02:11 UTC)\n- telegram:group:-5168104492 (DTLX Ecosystem Group): running, ACTIVE — senior-frontend still running, 3x senior-backend failed/killed\n\n**Current state (02:53 UTC):**\nLooking at what's changed: cron:6f3323ef is still running with the DTLX 5p Monitor, and cron:ed2d0b5d (QLHV 5p monitor) is also still running.\n\nThe cron:e7885813 (Agent Status) has a new session ID, and cron:ac986a8d remains orphaned at around 23.5 hours stale. The main heartbeat check came back OK at 02:17 UTC. The direct Telegram session to 6053576134 ended at 02:37 UTC after 8886ms, and there's another cron job (e7885813) that started at 02:44 UTC and is currently running. The DTLX group Telegram session is still active, and I'm seeing more child sessions being tracked.\n\nThe key insight is that the direct Telegram session ending is actually a state change worth reporting—previously it was marked as running and idle, but now it's ended. The DTLX 5p monitor has been running for about 9 hours since it started at 20:44 UTC. Looking at the timestamp conversions and session details more carefully—the DTLX session was started at 1776220844878 (02:47 UTC), not 20:44 as I initially thought, which aligns it with the current time of 02:53 UTC, so that session is only about 6 minutes old, not 9 hours. I'm calculating the session age for cron:6f3323ef — it started around 20:44 UTC on April 14, which would make it about 6 hours old at 02:53 UTC on April 15, though there's a slight discrepancy in the heartbeat timestamp I need to verify.\n\nNow looking at the state changes since the last report at 02:46 UTC: the Agent Status session got a new cycle with a different session ID but the same cron job key, the Telegram direct session ended, and the DTLX ecosystem session is actively running with child agents including prompt-optimizer, senior-backend, and senior-frontend all doing work. I should update the heartbeat state to reflect these changes. The Telegram direct session ended and the agent status completed a cycle, which are meaningful changes I should report. The DTLX Ecosystem session is actively running with its child sessions, and the orphaned cron is still unresolved from before—I'll document these state changes in the report and update the heartbeat file.\n\nFormatting the summary now with the timestamp, session counts, and status across the different environments and services.\n\nI'm verifying the cron timing discrepancy—the agent status cron ran at 02:44 UTC according to the messages, but the heartbeat state shows the previous cycle completed at 02:28 UTC, so there's about a 16-minute gap I need to account for. Looking at the Telegram direct session ending, I can see the QLHV ecosystem group was still active with its monitoring cron jobs and report timestamps, so I'll include this as a minor state change in the update. Since the main session is still running, I can update the heartbeat state file directly from here rather than trying to call the memory tool.","thinkingSignature":"112917876d405883ba90b7000e96a55ed1da946d2ba47d168f3281d9b6f12006"},{"type":"text","text":"Comparing against last state (02:46 UTC), I can see meaningful changes: the Telegram direct session (Lead poll) has ended, and the DTLX Ec